# SOLID principles

Follow SOLID when writing or refactoring code. Prefer small, focused types over kitchen-sink modules.

- **S — Single Responsibility**: One reason to change per type/module. Split UI, data access, and domain logic.
- **O — Open/Closed**: Extend via new types/composition; avoid editing stable code paths for every variant.
- **L — Liskov Substitution**: Subtypes must honor the parent contract; no surprise behavior in overrides.
- **I — Interface Segregation**: Prefer narrow protocols/interfaces over fat ones callers only partly use.
- **D — Dependency Inversion**: Depend on abstractions (`CollectionRepository`), not concrete SwiftData types, at feature boundaries.

```swift
// ❌ BAD — view owns persistence + filtering + drag + share rendering
struct ExchangeView: View { /* scans catalog, saves models, builds share images */ }

// ✅ GOOD — view composes focused collaborators
struct ExchangeView: View {
    @State private var viewModel = ExchangeViewModel() // list derivation
    @State private var dragController = ExchangeDragController() // drag only
}
```

When a change would force a type to grow a second responsibility, extract first.
